</script>

Salt makes food taste better. Too much ruins it. Color works the same way. Use it intentionally, not just to "make things pop."

## Two Extremes (Both Wrong)

1. **Too little color:** Everything gray. Functional but lifeless. No energy, no direction.
2. **Too much color:** Every section a different background, every button a different color. Feels like a confetti explosion.

The sweet spot is in between: *meaningful* color that earns its place.

## When Color Actually Works

- **Interactive elements:** Your primary color on buttons and links signals "click me."
- **Status communication:** Green = good. Red = bad. Yellow = attention. These are universal.
- **Brand moments:** A subtle splash of brand color reinforces identity without screaming.
- **Grouping:** A light tinted background can group a section without being loud.

## When Color is Just Noise

- Coloring a heading to "make it interesting"
- Different background colors for sections that mean the same thing
- Colorful icons where gray would work just as well
- Rainbow navigation with every item in a different color (please don't)

Color used to decorate, not communicate, is just noise.

